rounds.response:
Let’s re-evaluate our bargaining position.

What I learned from the last turns  
- Player 1 desperately wants Ore (they kept trying to give Wheat/Wood for Ore).  
- Brick has by far the smallest supply (only 8), making it the scarcest object in my hand.  
- The values I put on every unit are simply the marginal value the program printed (Wheat 5, Wood 10, Sheep 15, Brick 28, Ore 34).

Quick check of current totals  

Before any move  
105 Wheat, 240 Wood, 210 Sheep, 224 Brick, 612 Ore  
Total: 1 191

My objective is a strictly higher total after any accepted trade.  
I can happily lose 1-3 units of Ore or Brick because the marginal value table decays as we hold more.  
However I should never give away Brick below my printed value ≈28.

Possible simple win-win  
Give 2 Ore (marginal value 34 each ≈ 68) for 3 Brick (marginal ≈ 3 × 28 = 84) – value gain +16 in my reading, very easy for P1 to agree to because they get their coveted Ore.

Round down numbers to sound fairer in chat.

[Offer: 2 Ore -> 3 Brick]
